<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-053-131 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 343 363</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Sept 26 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Japan: Nintendo craze sparks second game designer school. (Enix)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Miyazawa, Masayuki.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Enix (Training).andO;Topic:     Training of EmployeesProgramming InstructionProgrammersSoftware PublishersVideo gamesComputer games.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>JAPAN: NINTENDO CRAZE SPARKS SECOND GAME DESIGNER SCHOOL 09/26/91 TOKYO,JAPAN, 1991 SEP 26 (NB) -- Major game software developer Enix has becomesecond firm in Japan to create a school just to train programmers to writefor Nintendo game machines, including the wildly popular Family Computer.andO;Enix says the school will be ready for students by next April.andM;The game programmer school, to be located in Tokyo, is called Enix GameSchool.andP;  Daytime classes will be offered for students between the ages of 18and 23.andP;  The lessons will be offered for 6 hours a day and students willgraduate after one year.andM;For the initial year, the school is planning to accept 135 students.andP;  Theannual lesson fee will be 1.5 million yen ($11,000).andP;  Enix Game School willrequire students to master computer languages, graphic drawing, and gamescenario writing.andM;Many computer software firms including Enix have been suffering from ashortage of quality computer programmers.andP;  Creating one's own school to trainprogrammers is seen as a solution to the problem.andM;Enix will create a subsidiary to manage the school in Kawasaki next month.andO;The capitalization of the new firm will be 50 million yen ($370,000).andP;  Enixis the developer of the best-selling Family Computer games &quot;Dragon Quest&quot;series.andP;  It is said the firm has sold over 10 million units of the gamesoftware.andP;  Due to this success, the firm has recently listed its stocks onthe over-the- counter market at the Tokyo Stock Exchange.andM;(Masayuki Miyazawa/19910923/Press Contact: Enix, +81-3-3366-4251)</TEXT></DOC>